#CPUs Used for Crypto Miners
ğŸ“Œ Do miners use CPUs?
Yes â€” CPU mining was used in the early days of Bitcoin and is still used today for some cryptocurrencies, especially privacy-focused coins.

ğŸ”§ Types of CPUs Used for Mining
1ï¸âƒ£ Consumer CPUs (Desktop / Laptop CPUs)
These are common CPUs used by beginners.
Examples:
Intel Core i5 / i7 / i9
AMD Ryzen 5 / 7 / 9
Used for:
Small-scale mining
Coins like Monero (XMR)

2ï¸âƒ£ High-Core-Count CPUs (Best for Mining)
CPUs with many cores and threads are preferred.
Examples:
AMD Ryzen Threadripper
AMD EPYC
Intel Xeon
Why used?
More cores = more hash calculations
Better performance for CPU-friendly algorithms

3ï¸âƒ£ Server-Grade CPUs
Used in professional or industrial mining setups.
Examples:
AMD EPYC 7000 series
Intel Xeon Scalable processors
Used for:
Data-center-level mining
High uptime and stability

4ï¸âƒ£ ARM CPUs (Limited Use)
Low-power CPUs mainly for experiments.
Examples:
Raspberry Pi
ARM-based servers
Used for:
Learning and testing
Not profitable for mining

ğŸª™ Coins Commonly Mined Using CPUs
Monero (XMR)
Raptoreum (RTM)
VerusCoin (VRSC)
Haven Protocol (XHV)
(These use CPU-friendly algorithms like RandomX.)

âš ï¸ Important Note
Bitcoin is NOT mined using CPUs anymore
Bitcoin uses ASIC miners, not CPUs

â­ Key Takeaways (Very Important)
CPU mining uses general-purpose processors
Best CPUs have high core and thread counts
AMD CPUs are generally preferred over Intel for mining
CPU mining is suitable for privacy coins, not Bitcoin
CPU mining is less powerful than GPU or ASIC mining

What Type of Supercomputers Are Used for Mining?
ğŸ‘‰ Important truth first:
Traditional scientific supercomputers (like weather or nuclear research machines) are NOT used for crypto mining.
Instead, mining uses specialized high-performance computing systems, often called â€œsupercomputersâ€ because of their power.

ğŸ”‘ 1ï¸âƒ£ ASIC Mining Supercomputers (MOST IMPORTANT)
ğŸ“Œ What are they?
ASIC (Application-Specific Integrated Circuit) machines are the most powerful and efficient mining computers ever built.
They are designed only for mining, especially Bitcoin.

âš™ï¸ Versions / Examples (Bitcoin Mining)
Model	               Algorithm	            Hash Power
Antminer S19 Pro     	 SHA-256	             ~110 TH/s
Antminer S19 XP	       SHA-256	             ~140 TH/s
Antminer S21 (latest)	 SHA-256	             ~200+ TH/s
WhatsMiner M60        	SHA-256	             ~170 TH/s

âœ… These are considered mining supercomputers.

ğŸª™ Coins Mined
Bitcoin (BTC)
Bitcoin Cash (BCH)
Bitcoin SV (BSV)

ğŸ”‘ 2ï¸âƒ£ GPU Mining Rigs (Cluster-Based Supercomputers)
ğŸ“Œ What are they?
Large setups with hundreds or thousands of GPUs connected together (like a mini-supercomputer).
Used before Ethereum moved to Proof of Stake.

âš™ï¸ Versions / Examples
GPU Model	Company
NVIDIA RTX 3090	
NVIDIA RTX 4090	
AMD RX 6800 XT	
AMD RX 7900 XTX	
ğŸ§  When clustered together, they act like a parallel supercomputer.

ğŸª™ Coins Mined
Ethereum Classic (ETC)
Ravencoin (RVN)
Ergo (ERG)

ğŸ”‘ 3ï¸âƒ£ CPU-Based Supercomputer Clusters (Rare)
ğŸ“Œ What are they?
Clusters of high-core CPUs connected like supercomputers.

âš™ï¸ Versions / Examples
AMD EPYC 7003 / 9004
Intel Xeon Scalable

ğŸª™ Coins Mined
Monero (XMR)
VerusCoin (VRSC)
âš ï¸ Used only for CPU-friendly algorithms.

âŒ 4ï¸âƒ£ Scientific Supercomputers (NOT USED)
Examples:
Summit (USA)
Fugaku (Japan)
PARAM Siddhi (India)

âŒ Not used for mining because:
Very expensive electricity
Government-controlled
Not energy-efficient for mining

â­ Key Takeaways (VERY IMPORTANT)
Bitcoin mining uses ASIC supercomputers
Latest versions: Antminer S19 XP, S21
GPUs are used in large clusters, not single PCs
CPUs are used only for privacy coins
Scientific supercomputers are not used for crypto mining
